../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:662:## `SKILL.md` format
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:664:The `SKILL.md` file must contain YAML frontmatter followed by Markdown content.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:680:  ```markdown SKILL.md theme={null}
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:689:  ```markdown SKILL.md theme={null}
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:849:Note that the agent will load this entire file once it's decided to activate a skill. Consider splitting longer `SKILL.md` content into referenced files.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:886:2. **Instructions** (\< 5000 tokens recommended): The full `SKILL.md` body is loaded when the skill is activated
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:889:Keep your main `SKILL.md` under 500 lines. Move detailed reference material to separate files.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:895:```markdown SKILL.md theme={null}
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:902:Keep file references one level deep from `SKILL.md`. Avoid deeply nested reference chains.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:906:Use the [skills-ref](https://github.com/agentskills/agentskills/tree/main/skills-ref) reference library to validate your skills:
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:909:skills-ref validate ./my-skill
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:912:This checks that your `SKILL.md` frontmatter is valid and follows all naming conventions.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:916:> Fetch the complete documentation index at: https://agentskills.io/llms.txt
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:923:A skill only helps if it gets activated. The `description` field in your `SKILL.md` frontmatter is the primary mechanism agents use to decide whether to load a skill for a given task. An under-specified description means the skill won't trigger when it should; an over-broad description means it triggers when it shouldn't.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:929:Agents use [progressive disclosure](/specification#progressive-disclosure) to manage context. At startup, they load only the `name` and `description` of each available skill — just enough to decide when a skill might be relevant. When a user's task matches a description, the agent reads the full `SKILL.md` into context and follows its instructions.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:995:Most agent clients provide some form of observability — execution logs, tool call histories, or verbose output — that lets you see which skills were consulted during a run. Check your client's documentation for details. The skill triggered if the agent loaded your skill's `SKILL.md`; it didn't trigger if the agent proceeded without consulting it.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:1087:1. Update the `description` field in your `SKILL.md` frontmatter.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:1114:> Fetch the complete documentation index at: https://agentskills.io/llms.txt
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:1162:Once a skill activates, its full `SKILL.md` body loads into the agent's context window alongside conversation history, system context, and other active skills. Every token in your skill competes for the agent's attention with everything else in that window.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:1202:The [specification](/specification#progressive-disclosure) recommends keeping `SKILL.md` under 500 lines and 5,000 tokens — just the core instructions the agent needs on every run. When a skill legitimately needs more content, move detailed reference material to separate files in `references/` or similar directories.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:1295:Keep gotchas in `SKILL.md` where the agent reads them before encountering the situation. A separate reference file works if you tell the agent when to load it, but for non-obvious issues, the agent may not recognize the trigger.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:1303:When you need the agent to produce output in a specific format, provide a template. This is more reliable than describing the format in prose, because agents pattern-match well against concrete structures. Short templates can live inline in `SKILL.md`; for longer templates, or templates only needed in certain cases, store them in `assets/` and reference them from `SKILL.md` so they only load when needed.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:1336:- [ ] Step 3: Validate mapping (run `scripts/validate_fields.py`)
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:1343:Instruct the agent to validate its own work before moving on. The pattern is: do the work, run a validator (a script, a reference checklist, or a self-check), fix any issues, and repeat until validation passes.
../org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log:1349:2. Run validation: `python scripts/validate.py output/`
